message:
Bob —

Below are concise, non-UI methods you can use to (A) list the branches in a repo and (B) determine which branch is the repository’s default. I show both GitLab API (preferred for authoritative info) and plain Git commands (works without API access). Replace https://gitlab.example with your GitLab server URL and root/theagentcompany are the credentials you supplied.

1) Using the GitLab REST API (authoritative)
- What you’ll use:
  - GET /projects/:id — contains default_branch
  - GET /projects/:id/repository/branches — lists branches and metadata

- Get the project id (or use URL-encoded namespace/project path)
  - If you know namespace/repo name, URL-encode it (slash -> %2F):
    - Example: namespace "root" and repo "my-repo" => root%2Fmy-repo
  - Example curl to inspect project metadata (shows default_branch):
    curl --user root:theagentcompany \
      "https://gitlab.example/api/v4/projects/root%2Fmy-repo" | jq '.id, .default_branch'

  - If you don’t know the project path, search projects:
    curl --user root:theagentcompany \
      "https://gitlab.example/api/v4/projects?search=my-repo" | jq '.[].id, .[].path_with_namespace'

- List all branches for the project:
  curl --user root:theagentcompany \
    "https://gitlab.example/api/v4/projects/root%2Fmy-repo/repository/branches" | jq '.[] | {name: .name, protected: .protected, merged: .merged}'

  Interpretation:
  - The project object (GET /projects/:id) has "default_branch": that string is the default branch.
  - The branches endpoint returns branch objects (name, protected, merged, commit, etc.). Use the default_branch value to pick the default.

Notes about authentication:
- The above uses HTTP Basic (--user username:password) with the credentials you provided. If your GitLab version or policy disallows basic auth to the API, you’ll need a personal access token (PRIVATE-TOKEN header). You can create tokens in the UI or via admin rails console if UI isn’t available (requires admin access).

2) Using only Git (no API)
- If you can access the repository URL (HTTP(S) or SSH), these will show branches and the remote HEAD mapping.

- Show remote branches (fast):
  git ls-remote --heads https://gitlab.example/root/my-repo.git

  Output example:
  e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb92427ae41e4  refs/heads/feature/foo
  9f86d081884c7d659a2feaa0c55ad015a3bf4f1b  refs/heads/main

- Show the remote’s symbolic HEAD (this tells you the default branch):
  git ls-remote --symref https://gitlab.example/root/my-repo.git HEAD

  Example output when default is main:
  ref: refs/heads/main HEAD
  9f86d081884c7d659a2feaa0c55ad015a3bf4f1b  HEAD

  Interpretation:
  - The "ref: refs/heads/<branch> HEAD" line indicates which branch is the remote HEAD — that branch is the default branch.

- If you already have a local clone with remote named origin:
  git remote show origin

  Look for the line "HEAD branch: <name>" which is the default branch.
  git branch -r
  lists remote branches.

3) Quick scriptable checks (examples)
- API (get default branch only):
  curl --silent --user root:theagentcompany "https://gitlab.example/api/v4/projects/root%2Fmy-repo" | jq -r '.default_branch'

- Git (get default branch directly from remote HEAD):
  git ls-remote --symref https://gitlab.example/root/my-repo.git HEAD 2>/dev/null | awk '/^ref:/ {print $2}' | sed 's@refs/heads/@@'

4) Extra useful info
- Protected branches: GitLab API returns .protected for branches; useful for cleanup decisions.
- Merged/stale: Branch objects can show whether merged (or check commit date) via API/commit info.
- If UI is unavailable and you cannot create a personal access token, use the git methods which only require HTTP(S)/SSH read access.
- Replace jq piped usage with plain parsing if jq is not installed.

If you want, tell me:
- the exact GitLab server URL and the repository path (namespace/repo), and whether you prefer using the API or plain git — I can produce exact commands and parse the outputs for you.
